 just to prove that you're intellectually superior,

251
00:09:45,540 --> 00:09:46,860
 which Christians, we never do that, do we?

252
00:09:46,860 --> 00:09:48,100
 We don't do that with one another.

253
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:49,540
 We don't do that with the world.

254
00:09:49,540 --> 00:09:50,860
 And yet the reality is,

255
00:09:50,860 --> 00:09:52,820
 it doesn't mean we shouldn't disagree with people.

256
00:09:52,820 --> 00:09:54,460
 It doesn't mean that we can't be corrective

257
00:09:54,460 --> 00:09:55,300
 in conversations.

258
00:09:55,300 --> 00:09:56,780
 But what it does tell us

259
00:09:56,780 --> 00:10:00,220
 is that we should be aware

260
00:10:00,220 --> 00:10:02,860
 if ever we're lobbing verbal bombs

261
00:10:02,860 --> 00:10:05,140
 and it feels like the conversation has caught fire

262
00:10:05,140 --> 00:10:08,180
 and nothing is going productively.

263
00:10:08,180 --> 00:10:11,860
 That tells us we're in the midst of a word war.

264
00:10:11,860 --> 00:10:14,860
 So as just an example,

265
00:10:14,860 --> 00:10:17,700
 in marriage, often, not always,

266
00:10:17,700 --> 00:10:20,180
 but often, your biggest disagreements

267
00:10:20,180 --> 00:10:23,600
 always come from the smallest of issues.

268
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:24,780
 I remember for Brooke and I,

269
00:10:24,780 --> 00:10:26,720
 it was early in our marriage

270
00:10:26,720 --> 00:10:29,340
 and the week was long, it was difficult.

271
00:10:29,340 --> 00:10:30,860
 We were finally at the weekend.

272
00:10:30,860 --> 00:10:31,860
 And so we were like, you know what?

273
00:10:31,860 --> 00:10:33,220
 Let's bring it in the right way.

274
00:10:33,220 --> 00:10:35,820
 Let's prep dinner and let's grill some steaks

275
00:10:35,820 --> 00:10:37,900
 and start the weekend on a high note.

276
00:10:37,900 --> 00:10:40,700
 Now, unashamedly, steak is my favorite food.

277
00:10:40,700 --> 00:10:44,740
 I mean, it is by and large, Kylen Perry's favorite meal.

278
00:10:44,740 --> 00:10:47,500
 It is my preference if ever I get to pick.

279
00:10:47,500 --> 00:10:49,260
 And so we were doing this this night.

280
00:10:49,260 --> 00:10:52,420
 And now as any self-respecting person knows,

281
00:10:52,420 --> 00:10:56,300
 steak is always served with potatoes, always.

282
00:10:56,300 --> 00:10:58,140
 Like that's a non-negotiable.

283
00:10:58,140 --> 00:11:00,300
 It is assumed at the very least.

284
00:11:00,300 --> 00:11:01,860
 And yet for whatever reason,

285
00:11:01,860 --> 00:11:04,780
 my wife did not seem to know this.

286
00:11:04,780 --> 00:11:06,900
 She had not purchased any potatoes to speak of.

287
00:11:06,900 --> 00:11:09,860
 Instead, she had decided that we would eat corn and salad

288
00:11:09,860 --> 00:11:12,500
 alongside that steak in the evening.

289
00:11:12,500 --> 00:11:15,580
 And what ensued from that moment

290
00:11:15,580 --> 00:11:17,820
 was the equivalent of a word war

291
00:11:17,820 --> 00:11:22,540
 because I unpinned a verbal grenade and I lobbed it at her.

292
00:11:22,540 --> 00:11:24,040
 And I was like, are you crazy?

293
00:11:24,940 --> 00:11:28,860
 Like steak without potatoes, we might as well not even eat.

294
00:11:28,860 --> 00:11:32,300
 Marriage is so very sanctifying.

295
00:11:32,300 --> 00:11:33,660
 This is case in point number one.

296
00:11:33,660 --> 00:11:36,180
 I have since grown so very much.

297
00:11:36,180 --> 00:11:40,620
 And you would never, never engage in something

298
00:11:40,620 --> 00:11:42,500
 so seemingly silly as that.

299
00:11:42,500 --> 00:11:47,260
 And yet often we do engage,

300
00:11:47,260 --> 00:11:49,420
 we fight over something so seemingly serious

301
00:11:49,420 --> 00:11:52,280
 as whether or not true believers can be tempted

302
00:11:52,280 --> 00:11:54,180
 with same-sex attraction or not.

303
00:11:55,180 --> 00:11:59,460
 Whether you're allowed or not allowed

304
00:11:59,460 --> 00:12:02,260
 to vote Democrat and love Jesus at the same time,

305
00:12:02,260 --> 00:12:06,260
 whether Charlie Kirk is or isn't actually a Christian martyr,

306
00:12:06,260 --> 00:12:08,180
 whether you should or you shouldn't.

307
00:12:08,180 --> 00:12:11,540
 Listen to Chapel Rome if you are a Christian.

308
00:12:11,540 --> 00:12:14,300
 Here's the thing.

309
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:17,540
 I haven't even stated to you my position

310
00:12:17,540 --> 00:12:18,960
 on some of these issues,

311
00:12:18,960 --> 00:12:21,860
 but the mere mention of them

312
00:12:21,860 --> 00:12:24,460
 has some of you boiling inside,

313
00:12:24,460 --> 00:12:28,700
 ready to spring into action and present your case.

314
00:12:28,700 --> 00:12:33,360
 And that is evidence of a quarrelsome heart.

315
00:12:33,360 --> 00:12:37,260
 Now, am I saying that these things

316
00:12:37,260 --> 00:12:38,560
 are not worthy of talking about?

317
00:12:38,560 --> 00:12:39,400
 Of course not.

318
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:41,000
 That's not what I'm saying in the slightest,

319
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,180
 but I am saying the way we talk about them

320
00:12:44,180 --> 00:12:47,500
 matters quite possibly even more.

321
00:12:48,660 --> 00:12:49,700
 Verse Peter 3:15 says,

322
00:12:49,700 --> 00:12:53,580
 "But in your hearts honor Christ the Lord as holy,

323
00:12:53,580 --> 00:12:55,820
 always being prepared to make a defense.

324
00:12:55,820 --> 00:12:58,900
 Do it for anyone who asks you for a reason

325
00:12:58,900 --> 00:12:59,740
 for the hope that's in you,

326
00:12:59,740 --> 00:13:03,780
 and yet do it with gentleness and respect."

327
00:13:03,780 --> 00:13:05,020
 Do you see it?

328
00:13:05,020 --> 00:13:08,100
 We should always be prepared to make a defense.

329
00:13:08,100 --> 00:13:10,520
 That's the what, and yet Peter doesn't stop there.

330
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:11,360
 He gives you the how.

331
00:13:11,360 --> 00:13:13,700
 He says, "You should be prepared to make a defense,

332
00:13:13,700 --> 00:13:17,440
 but not a destructive one.

333
00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:21,100
 You should prepare instead to make a constructive defense."

334
00:13:21,100 --> 00:13:24,260
 It's interesting, in the passage we're looking at,

335
00:13:24,260 --> 00:13:26,580
 when he says, "Rightly handling the word of truth,"

336
00:13:26,580 --> 00:13:30,620
 the idea there is that you would cut a straight line

337
00:13:30,620 --> 00:13:32,240
 in the original language.

338
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:34,980
 It would be used as characteristic of a carpenter

339
00:13:34,980 --> 00:13:38,060
 or a seamstress or a master craftsman.

340
00:13:38,060 --> 00:13:40,860
 It would tell you that they are an expert

341
00:13:40,860 --> 00:13:42,580
 in their particular trade.

342
00:13:42,580 --> 00:13:45,500
 They can constructively contribute

343
00:13:45,500 --> 00:13:48,300
 to whatever their field of expertise is.

344
00:13:48,300 --> 00:13:51,220
 For the Christian, what is our field of expertise?

345
00:13:51,220 --> 00:13:54,060
 It's God's word.

346
00:13:54,060 --> 00:13:56,260
 It's not the stock market.

347
00:13:56,260 --> 00:13:58,860
 It's not how to make the best sourdough.

348
00:13:58,860 --> 00:14:01,140
 It's not who are the studs and duds

349
00:14:01,140 --> 00:14:03,220
 of week four fantasy football.

350
00:14:03,220 --> 00:14:05,660
 It's not whether or not you're actually gonna be able

351
00:14:05,660 --> 00:14:06,820
 to shoot a shot at Robert Irwin

352
00:14:06,820 --> 00:14:08,820
 because you think he's so cute on "Dancing with the Stars."

353
00:14:08,820 --> 00:14:12,340
 None of that is actually your field of expertise.

354
00:14:12,340 --> 00:14:13,600
 No, our field of expertise

355
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:18,420
 is what does the word of God say?

356
00:14:18,420 --> 00:14:19,940
 And yet here's the thing,

357
00:14:19,940 --> 00:14:21,840
 rather than being an expert in God's word,

358
00:14:21,840 --> 00:14:25,640
 too often we are an expert in someone else's words.

359
00:14:25,640 --> 00:14:29,900
 Culturally, we know better what our favorite teachers think

360
00:14:29,900 --> 00:14:31,540
 or our podcaster's position is

361
00:14:31,540 --> 00:14:33,740
 or that influencer has to say.

362
00:14:33,740 --> 00:14:36,020
 We have mastered the opinions of man

363
00:14:36,020 --> 00:14:38,400
 and not the truth of God.

364
00:14:38,400 --> 00:14:40,780
 For Christians, we're not exempt.

365
00:14:40,780 --> 00:14:42,420
 In fact, we are more guilty

366
00:14:42,420 --> 00:14:45,540
 of having been raised under generational voices

367
00:14:45,540 --> 00:14:49,720
 of adopting what our favorite pastors think about Jesus

368
00:14:49,720 --> 00:14:52,300
 rather than what we think of Jesus himself.

369
00:14:52,300 --> 00:14:54,760
 You see, we are willing to live vicariously

370
00:14:54,760 --> 00:14:57,520
 through the relationship someone else has with Christ

371
00:14:57,520 --> 00:15:00,920
 when we forego the ability to have that own relationship

372
00:15:00,920 --> 00:15:03,180
 within our own lives.

373
00:15:03,180 --> 00:15:05,880
 And yet the truth of the matter is

374
00:15:05,880 --> 00:15:08,380
 you're not called to be an expert in anybody else's words

375
00:15:08,380 --> 00:15:09,220
 nor their opinions.

376
00:15:09,220 --> 00:15:12,040
 You're meant to be an expert in God's word.

377
00:15:12,040 --> 00:15:15,740
 That's why we go deep in this book.

378
00:15:15,740 --> 00:15:18,140
 All the questions facing humanity,

379
00:15:18,140 --> 00:15:20,940
 the answers are right here.

380
00:15:20,940 --> 00:15:24,460
 That's why we show up and we attend a Bible study

381
00:15:24,460 --> 00:15:26,420
 and we surround ourselves with men and women

382
00:15:26,420 --> 00:15:28,420
 that are older and wiser than we are.

383
00:15:28,420 --> 00:15:30,620
 It's why we choose to every single day

384
00:15:30,620 --> 00:15:32,900
 invest in reading this

385
00:15:32,900 --> 00:15:36,100
 because we know in it is all the truth we need

386
00:15:36,100 --> 00:15:37,620
 for the life we live.

387
00:15:37,620 --> 00:15:40,620
 It's why we don't just fake it till we make it

388
00:15:40,620 --> 00:15:42,760
 or we act like we have all the answers.

389
00:15:42,760 --> 00:15:44,600
 We're willing to look dumb and ask questions,

390
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:45,800
 go to great questions,

391
00:15:45,800 --> 00:15:48,080
 impose some of the things that we're really wondering

392
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:50,280
 and even worried about because we wanna know,

393
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:51,520
 man, what does God have to say

394
00:15:51,520 --> 00:15:53,760
 about these specific issues in our life?

395
00:15:53,760 --> 00:15:55,480
 It's why we're willing to go to a church

396
00:15:55,480 --> 00:15:56,840
 that teaches the Bible.

397
00:15:56,840 --> 00:15:58,840
 And listen to me, some of you need to be willing

398
00:15:58,840 --> 00:16:02,760
 to leave a church that does not teach the Bible.

399
00:16:02,760 --> 00:16:04,760
 I'm not telling you to come here,

400
00:16:04,760 --> 00:16:06,520
 but I'm telling you to go somewhere

401
00:16:06,520 --> 00:16:09,440
 that rightly reveres the word of God

402
00:16:09,440 --> 00:16:12,920
 as the ultimate authority in all matters.

403
00:16:12,920 --> 00:16:15,420
 I remember for myself in college,

404
00:16:15,420 --> 00:16:18,740
 every night I would sit for a season

405
00:16:18,740 --> 00:16:21,920
 and I would read small sections of scripture.

406
00:16:21,920 --> 00:16:25,460
 And in order to understand them,

407
00:16:25,460 --> 00:16:28,820
 I would write them back in my own words.

408
00:16:28,820 --> 00:16:30,540
 I have journals filled with the KLP,

409
00:16:30,540 --> 00:16:32,660
 the Kyle and Levi Perry translation.

410
00:16:32,660 --> 00:16:35,260
 And it would just give me a way

411
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:37,260
 of trying to really understand

412
00:16:37,260 --> 00:16:39,220
 in through my own articulation

413
00:16:39,220 --> 00:16:40,640
 the very words that God had spoken.

414
00:16:40,640 --> 00:16:42,640
 And here's the crazy thing, as I did it,

415
00:16:42,640 --> 00:16:45,480
 the book came alive.

416
00:16:45,480 --> 00:16:50,020
 It wasn't just that I was reading passages any longer,

417
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:53,500
 it's that God was speaking those passages to me.

418
00:16:53,500 --> 00:16:58,500
 I realized that this book isn't dead, it's living.

419
00:16:58,500 --> 00:17:02,940
 It's speaking and it's changing me

420
00:17:02,940 --> 00:17:04,740
 and it can change you too.

421
00:17:04,740 --> 00:17:08,300
 We must become an expert in the word of God.

422
00:17:08,300 --> 00:17:10,740
 We need to know what we believe,

423
00:17:10,740 --> 00:17:12,140
 because then if we don't,

424
00:17:12,140 --> 00:17:13,620
 we'll struggle with what Paul says next.

425
00:17:13,620 --> 00:17:15,740
 Let's keep going, verse 16.

426
00:17:15,740 --> 00:17:18,380
 "But avoid irreverent babble.

427
00:17:18,380 --> 00:17:20,500
 "It'll lead people into more and more ungodliness

428
00:17:20,500 --> 00:17:22,880
 "and their talk will spread like gangrene.

429
00:17:22,880 --> 00:17:25,880
 "Among them are Hymenaeus and Philetus

430
00:17:25,880 --> 00:17:27,520
 "who have swerved from the truth,

431
00:17:27,520 --> 00:17:29,620
 "saying that the resurrection has already happened.

432
00:17:29,620 --> 00:17:30,940
 "They're upsetting the faith of some,

433
00:17:30,940 --> 00:17:33,100
 "but God's firm foundation stands bearing the seal.

434
00:17:33,100 --> 00:17:35,420
 "The Lord knows who are his

435
00:17:35,420 --> 00:17:37,140
 "and let everyone who names the name of the Lord

436
00:17:37,140 --> 00:17:39,700
 "depart from iniquity."

437
00:17:39,700 --> 00:17:40,900
 The second thing that Paul teaches us,

438
00:17:40,900 --> 00:17:43,780
 if we wanna live a life that is honorable,

439
00:17:43,780 --> 00:17:47,620
 is we should guard against ungodly influences.

440
00:17:47,620 --> 00:17:50,580
 Guard against ungodly influences.

441
00:17:50,580 --> 00:17:53,540
 He says that these false teachers,

442
00:17:53,540 --> 00:17:55,620
 they speak irreverent babble,

443
00:17:55,620 --> 00:17:56,620
 which I don't know about you,

444
00:17:56,620 --> 00:17:58,300
 but for me, it was a little difficult to understand.

445
00:17:58,300 --> 00:18:00,580
 Like, what does that actually even mean?

446
00:18:00,580 --> 00:18:01,900
 And so the way we understand it

447
00:18:01,900 --> 00:18:03,060
 is just taking it word by word

448
00:18:03,060 --> 00:18:04,620
 and trying to really parse through

449
00:18:04,620 --> 00:18:08,020
 what they are definitionally interpreted as.

450
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:09,500
 And so if you think about the word irreverent,

451
00:18:09,500 --> 00:18:11,860
 irreverent means it's disrespectful

452
00:18:11,860 --> 00:18:14,540
 or it's inappropriate or it's improper.

453
00:18:14,540 --> 00:18:17,220
 Like, it would be going to an interview

454
00:18:17,220 --> 00:18:19,580
 and wearing swim trunks.

455
00:18:19,580 --> 00:18:20,980
 There's nothing wrong with an interview.

456
00:18:20,980 --> 00:18:22,380
 There's nothing wrong with swim trunks,

457
00:18:22,380 --> 00:18:24,180
 but they are very wrong together.

458
00:18:24,180 --> 00:18:27,340
 That is an inappropriate sort of situation.

459
00:18:27,340 --> 00:18:29,540
 That's what it looks like to be irreverent.

460
00:18:29,540 --> 00:18:33,700
 That word babble, it's the idea of nonsense.

461
00:18:33,700 --> 00:18:37,380
 So our baby boy, Cash, he is almost a year old,

462
00:18:37,380 --> 00:18:38,660
 but in the last few months,

463
00:18:38,660 --> 00:18:41,540
 he's really started babbling quite a lot.

464
00:18:41,540 --> 00:18:45,020
 And while adorable, it is absolute nonsense.

465
00:18:45,020 --> 00:18:46,940
 He looked at a squirrel today and said, "Da-da."

466
00:18:46,940 --> 00:18:48,740
 I mean, you know, it's like, dude, that's not your da-da.

467
00:18:48,740 --> 00:18:49,580
 I'm your da-da.

468
00:18:49,580 --> 00:18:51,420
 Like, that is just noise coming out of you.

469
00:18:51,420 --> 00:18:55,540
 You're not making any kind of sense whatsoever.

470
00:18:55,540 --> 00:18:57,140
 Paul is saying there are a lot of people in the world

471
00:18:57,140 --> 00:18:59,020
 that are making noise.

472
00:18:59,020 --> 00:19:02,500
 A lot of people in the world that speak nonsense.

473
00:19:02,500 --> 00:19:07,500
 Timothy and Christian do not listen to them.

474
00:19:07,500 --> 00:19:14,540
 They may sound convincing, but they will not be convicting

475
00:19:14,540 --> 00:19:17,340
 because there's not an ounce of truth

476
00:19:17,340 --> 00:19:18,860
 in the things that they say.

477
00:19:18,860 --> 00:19:23,020
 That's why they're called false teachers.

478
00:19:23,020 --> 00:19:23,900
 And here's the thing,

479
00:19:23,900 --> 00:19:26,520
 they didn't just exist in Timothy's day.

480
00:19:26,520 --> 00:19:29,700
 They exist, and maybe even in greater degree,

481
00:19:29,700 --> 00:19:32,380
 within our own right now.

482
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:34,620
 This isn't just something that we look at in the text

483
00:19:34,620 --> 00:19:36,660
 and we realize it was a problem for them there.

484
00:19:36,660 --> 00:19:38,460
 No, it's something we look at in our lives

485
00:19:38,460 --> 00:19:40,920
 and we realize it is a problem here now.

486
00:19:40,920 --> 00:19:44,980
 And it's in greater degree than we likely even suspect,

487
00:19:44,980 --> 00:19:48,140
 because what you realize is people can, via social media,

488
00:19:48,140 --> 00:19:51,340
 gather crowds and assemble followers

489
00:19:51,340 --> 00:19:53,900
 and disseminate whatever they wanna teach,

490
00:19:53,900 --> 00:19:57,040
 whatever dreams they have, whatever thoughts they think,

491
00:19:57,040 --> 00:19:58,420
 whatever words they've received,

492
00:19:58,420 --> 00:20:00,180
 whatever signs they can share.

493
00:20:00,180 --> 00:20:02,340
 That's what happens in social media.

494
00:20:02,340 --> 00:20:05,500
 And the crazy thing about it is people believe them.

495
00:20:05,500 --> 00:20:08,380
 They believe them because, well, they're not credible,

496
00:20:08,380 --> 00:20:10,660
 but they're approvable, they're popular,

497
00:20:10,660 --> 00:20:12,540
 they're trendy, and they're pretty,

498
00:20:12,540 --> 00:20:14,700
 and they're funny, and they're witty.

499
00:20:14,700 --> 00:20:17,300
 Instead, I'm gonna believe whatever they have to say

500
00:20:17,300 --> 00:20:19,740
 just because they're charismatic and intelligent.

501
00:20:19,740 --> 00:20:23,900
 Believer, we don't do that.

502
00:20:23,900 --> 00:20:27,540
 We don't just assume someone is speaking truth

503
00:20:27,540 --> 00:20:32,060
 because they're compelling in the way they speak it.

504
00:20:32,060 --> 00:20:34,460
 No, we listen to the words of John.

505
00:20:34,460 --> 00:20:35,300
 First John 4, one says,

506
00:20:35,300 --> 00:20:38,860
 "Beloved, do not believe every spirit,

507
00:20:38,860 --> 00:20:41,620
 "but test the spirits to see whether they're from God,

508
00:20:41,620 --> 00:20:46,620
 "for many false prophets have gone out into the world."

509
00:20:46,620 --> 00:20:47,960
 You hear it?

510
00:20:47,960 --> 00:20:51,800
 We don't trust spirits, we test spirits.

511
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:54,820
 We take anything anyone has ever said

512
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:58,220
 and we compare it against everything God has ever said,

513
00:20:58,220 --> 00:21:02,220
 and then we evaluate what is and is not true.

514
00:21:02,220 --> 00:21:06,700
 And the reason why we have to be vigilant in this

515
00:21:06,700 --> 00:21:08,540
 is there are so many people,

516
00:21:08,540 --> 00:21:11,500
 so many so-called Christians here today

517
00:21:11,500 --> 00:21:13,740
 that are willing to leverage the things of God

518
00:21:13,740 --> 00:21:15,880
 for their own personal gain.

519
00:21:15,880 --> 00:21:18,820
 And some of them, they're not hard to spot.

520
00:21:18,820 --> 00:21:22,300
 Christian thirst traps, they're suspect, man.

521
00:21:22,300 --> 00:21:25,220
 You know, you shouldn't really listen to those guys.

522
00:21:25,220 --> 00:21:26,060
 The guy who's like,

523
00:21:26,060 --> 00:21:27,880
 "The devil doesn't want you to keep scrolling,

524
00:21:27,880 --> 00:21:29,680
 "so stop," don't listen to him.

525
00:21:29,680 --> 00:21:31,500
 He's suspect as well.

526
00:21:31,500 --> 00:21:33,500
 Some TikTok prophets, you can look at them and say,

527
00:21:33,500 --> 00:21:37,220
 "Man, you seem like you are completely off the reservation."

528
00:21:37,220 --> 00:21:39,300
 And yet the truth of the matter is,

529
00:21:39,300 --> 00:21:40,660
 while there are some that are so obvious,

530
00:21:40,660 --> 00:21:44,440
 there are some that are not so obvious.

531
00:21:44,440 --> 00:21:45,940
 Listen to me.

532
00:21:45,940 --> 00:21:47,780
 I love you enough to say this to you.

533
00:21:47,780 --> 00:21:52,940
 Your therapist is not Jesus.

534
00:21:52,940 --> 00:21:56,180
 Can they be helpful?

535
00:21:56,180 --> 00:21:57,660
 Absolutely.

536
00:21:57,660 --> 00:22:00,320
 Are they necessary at times in life?

537
00:22:00,320 --> 00:22:02,060
 1,000%.

538
00:22:02,060 --> 00:22:03,420
 Would it serve you to have one?

539
00:22:03,420 --> 00:22:05,480
 I know it served me.

540
00:22:05,480 --> 00:22:06,940
 And yet the truth of the matter is,

541
00:22:06,940 --> 00:22:08,660
 just because your therapist says it

542
00:22:08,660 --> 00:22:10,520
 doesn't mean it's right.

543
00:22:10,520 --> 00:22:14,020
 It isn't confirmed as truth.

544
00:22:14,020 --> 00:22:18,260
 I have met young adults that have foregone

545
00:22:18,260 --> 00:22:20,860
 the biblical counsel of their community

546
00:22:20,860 --> 00:22:23,100
 and the convictions of God's own spirit

547
00:22:23,100 --> 00:22:26,160
 because their therapist disagreed and said so differently.

548
00:22:27,140 --> 00:22:30,780
 Listen, I'm not calling your therapist a false teacher.

549
00:22:30,780 --> 00:22:37,140
 But if they disagree with him, you disagree with them.

550
00:22:37,140 --> 00:22:40,700
 There's only one voice of truth,

551
00:22:40,700 --> 00:22:42,620
 and it is the voice of Jesus.

552
00:22:42,620 --> 00:22:43,580
 I'll give you another one.

553
00:22:43,580 --> 00:22:46,500
 Another good one is your favorite podcaster.

554
00:22:46,500 --> 00:22:48,360
 They aren't Jesus.

555
00:22:48,360 --> 00:22:50,180
 And look, I like podcasts.

556
00:22:50,180 --> 00:22:51,500
 I listen to them myself.

557
00:22:51,500 --> 00:22:53,540
 And yet what you have to know is it doesn't matter

558
00:22:53,540 --> 00:22:57,020
 how much self-help or personal development

559
00:22:57,020 --> 00:22:59,220
 they seem to offer, how many experts

560
00:22:59,220 --> 00:23:00,740
 they bring in and interview,

561
00:23:00,740 --> 00:23:03,920
 how much research they try to share.

562
00:23:03,920 --> 00:23:07,260
 It doesn't matter how convincing they may seem.

563
00:23:07,260 --> 00:23:09,500
 It doesn't make 'em right.

564
00:23:09,500 --> 00:23:12,220
 There's only been one man that's ever been right.

565
00:23:12,220 --> 00:23:14,220
 He was righteous for the unrighteous,

566
00:23:14,220 --> 00:23:16,660
 and his name was Jesus.

567
00:23:16,660 --> 00:23:19,780
 And so if your favorite podcaster disagrees with him,

568
00:23:19,780 --> 00:23:21,740
 then you disagree with them.

569
00:23:21,740 --> 00:23:23,540
 I'll give you one more.

570
00:23:23,540 --> 00:23:24,740
 This is not a comprehensive list,

571
00:23:24,740 --> 00:23:26,580
 but I do think these will be helpful

572
00:23:26,580 --> 00:23:29,060
 because these are really prevalent today.

573
00:23:29,060 --> 00:23:31,040
 Your political party isn't Jesus.

574
00:23:31,040 --> 00:23:33,260
 It's fascinating.

575
00:23:33,260 --> 00:23:36,420
 If you track the data that's really been coming out

576
00:23:36,420 --> 00:23:38,460
 in the articles surrounding it all,

577
00:23:38,460 --> 00:23:42,100
 there is a resurgence of young men

578
00:23:42,100 --> 00:23:43,160
 coming back to the church.

579
00:23:43,160 --> 00:23:45,580
 They're actually outpacing young women

580
00:23:45,580 --> 00:23:50,260
 in their involvement within religious spaces like this.

581
00:23:50,260 --> 00:23:51,660
 And yet according to some publications,

582
00:23:51,660 --> 00:23:53,500
 one being notably the New York Times,

583
00:23:53,500 --> 00:23:55,160
 so much of that spiritual resurgence

584
00:23:55,160 --> 00:23:58,900
 is tied to personal political preference.

585
00:23:58,900 --> 00:24:02,160
 In contrast, young women that are leaving the church,

586
00:24:02,160 --> 00:24:04,040
 they share the same cause.

587
00:24:04,040 --> 00:24:06,300
 They have personal political preference

588
00:24:06,300 --> 00:24:09,420
 that is leading them to do that instead.

589
00:24:09,420 --> 00:24:11,860
 Now, I'm not saying that it's wrong

590
00:24:11,860 --> 00:24:13,060
 to have political positions.

591
00:24:13,060 --> 00:24:14,420
 I think that you should have some,

592
00:24:14,420 --> 00:24:16,700
 you should consider God has given three institutions

593
00:24:16,700 --> 00:24:19,240
 in this world, the church, the family, and the government,

594
00:24:19,240 --> 00:24:21,600
 and so you need to understand what you think

595
00:24:21,600 --> 00:24:23,920
 when it comes to these areas and issues.

596
00:24:23,920 --> 00:24:25,420
 And what I would say though,

597
00:24:25,420 --> 00:24:28,760
 is that your political preference

598
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:31,980
 doesn't get to shape your beliefs about Jesus.

599
00:24:31,980 --> 00:24:33,380
 Your beliefs about Jesus

600
00:24:33,380 --> 00:24:37,500
 get to shape your political preferences.

601
00:24:37,500 --> 00:24:40,920
 If they disagree with him, you disagree with them.

602
00:24:40,920 --> 00:24:45,260
 Now, let me be abundantly clear

603
00:24:45,260 --> 00:24:47,780
 for the sake of avoiding some emails that may come my way.

604
00:24:47,780 --> 00:24:49,260
 I'm not saying you're a therapist,

605
00:24:49,260 --> 00:24:50,740
 I'm not saying you're a favorite podcaster,

606
00:24:50,740 --> 00:24:55,740
 and I'm not saying your political party is a false teacher.

607
00:24:55,740 --> 00:24:59,340
 But what I am saying

608
00:24:59,340 --> 00:25:03,820
 is that wolves still wear sheep's clothing.

609
00:25:03,820 --> 00:25:05,780
 And so they might sound convincing,

610
00:25:05,780 --> 00:25:08,420
 but you should not be so easily convinced.

611
00:25:08,420 --> 00:25:10,140
 Jesus says in Matthew 10, 16,

612
00:25:10,140 --> 00:25:14,860
 "Behold, I am sending you out as sheep in the midst of wolves

613
00:25:14,860 --> 00:25:19,860
 "so be wise as serpents and innocent as doves."

614
00:25:20,740 --> 00:25:23,660
 You be on guard, Christian,

615
00:25:23,660 --> 00:25:27,020
 and you hold fast to what's true.

616
00:25:27,020 --> 00:25:28,140
 You hold fast to him.

617
00:25:28,140 --> 00:25:32,580
 The next one Paul gives us is in 20 through 22.

618
00:25:32,580 --> 00:25:34,260
 He says, "Now in a great house,

619
00:25:34,260 --> 00:25:36,400
 "there are not only vessels of gold and silver,

620
00:25:36,400 --> 00:25:38,960
 "but also of wood and clay, some for honorable use,

621
00:25:38,960 --> 00:25:40,600
 "some for dishonorable use.

622
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:42,340
 "Therefore, if anyone cleanses himself

623
00:25:42,340 --> 00:25:43,900
 "from what is dishonorable,

624
00:25:43,900 --> 00:25:45,600
 "he'll be a vessel for honorable use,

625
00:25:45,600 --> 00:25:47,740
 "set apart as holy, useful to the master of the house,

626
00:25:47,740 --> 00:25:49,820
 "ready for every good work."

627
00:25:49,820 --> 00:25:52,940
 22, "So flee youthful passions and pursue righteousness,

628
00:25:52,940 --> 00:25:54,320
 "faith, love, and peace,

629
00:25:54,320 --> 00:25:57,980
 "along with those who call on the Lord from a pure heart."

630
00:25:57,980 --> 00:25:59,700
 The third thing that Paul wants you to know

631
00:25:59,700 --> 00:26:01,660
 if you wanna live an honorable life

632
00:26:01,660 --> 00:26:05,540
 is that you need to separate yourself from worldly passions.

633
00:26:05,540 --> 00:26:08,520
 You need to separate yourself from worldly passions.

634
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:11,300
 Now, admittedly, there's a lack of consensus

635
00:26:11,300 --> 00:26:13,420
 amongst scholars on what Paul means

636
00:26:13,420 --> 00:26:16,380
 whenever he uses this analogy of gold and silver vessels

637
00:26:16,380 --> 00:26:19,020
 versus those vessels of wood and clay instead.

638
00:26:19,020 --> 00:26:21,820
 Some people, they look at the analogy

639
00:26:21,820 --> 00:26:23,440
 and they think that it's characteristic

640
00:26:23,440 --> 00:26:24,780
 of believers and non-believers,

641
00:26:24,780 --> 00:26:27,340
 that there is a noble and ignoble use.

642
00:26:27,340 --> 00:26:29,200
 The other side of the fence would say

643
00:26:29,200 --> 00:26:31,240
 that it's not a reference to believer, non-believer,

644
00:26:31,240 --> 00:26:33,120
 it's a reference to different classes of believers,

645
00:26:33,120 --> 00:26:34,820
 those that are honorable and those that are dishonorable,

646
00:26:34,820 --> 00:26:36,780
 and yet all of them are vessels within the same house,

647
00:26:36,780 --> 00:26:40,700
 and so therefore, they are all saved by faith.

648
00:26:40,700 --> 00:26:41,860
 At the end of the day,

649
00:26:41,860 --> 00:26:44,500
 it does not matter what your interpretation is

650
00:26:44,500 --> 00:26:48,240
 because the takeaway is the same for both.

651
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:52,200
 We all want to be vessels of honor.

652
00:26:52,200 --> 00:26:53,360
 That's the takeaway.

653
00:26:53,360 --> 00:26:57,400
 You want to be a vessel of honorable use.

654
00:26:57,400 --> 00:26:59,200
 Like nobody wants to be a dog bowl.

655
00:26:59,200 --> 00:27:02,360
 Everybody wants to be fine china.

656
00:27:02,360 --> 00:27:03,200
 Why?

657
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:05,800
 Because a dog bowl, it sits on the ground,

658
00:27:05,800 --> 00:27:09,140
 it's likely chewed up, you don't wash it off in the sink,

659
00:27:09,140 --> 00:27:11,040
 you rinse it off with a water hose.

660
00:27:11,040 --> 00:27:11,920
 But if you think about fine china,

661
00:27:11,920 --> 00:27:14,600
 fine china is arranged in a cabinet,

662
00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:17,040
 it's put on display for all to see,

663
00:27:17,040 --> 00:27:20,480
 is only ever pulled out for the most distinguished of guests.

664
00:27:20,480 --> 00:27:23,040
 Now, is it true that you could use both

665
00:27:23,040 --> 00:27:24,960
 for the same purpose?

666
00:27:24,960 --> 00:27:26,960
 I guess.

667
00:27:26,960 --> 00:27:29,360
 But nobody wants you to do that.

668
00:27:29,360 --> 00:27:30,920
 Nobody wants you to pull out a dog bowl

669
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:32,680
 and serve them dinner in it.

670
00:27:32,680 --> 00:27:33,520
 Why?

671
00:27:33,520 --> 00:27:35,800
 Because that is not honorable, that is dishonorable,

672
00:27:35,800 --> 00:27:38,840
 that is deeply offensive.

673
00:27:38,840 --> 00:27:45,340
 God is pulling together believers for honorable purpose.

674
00:27:46,180 --> 00:27:47,620
 For honorable purpose.

675
00:27:47,620 --> 00:27:53,780
 For that which is important and special and distinct.

676
00:27:53,780 --> 00:27:56,740
 Don't you want that to be your story?

677
00:27:56,740 --> 00:27:59,800
 Then what you must do is you must cleanse yourself

678
00:27:59,800 --> 00:28:01,240
 of what is dishonorable.

679
00:28:01,240 --> 00:28:03,580
 How do you do that?

680
00:28:03,580 --> 00:28:05,160
 You do so in two different ways.

681
00:28:05,160 --> 00:28:06,380
 Paul tells us, number one,

682
00:28:06,380 --> 00:28:08,260
 you cleanse yourself of what is dishonorable,

683
00:28:08,260 --> 00:28:11,780
 and number two, you flee youthful passions and lusts.

684
00:28:11,780 --> 00:28:13,980
 He says you cleanse yourself of what's dishonorable.

685
00:28:13,980 --> 00:28:14,820
 I love this.

686
00:28:14,820 --> 00:28:15,740
 I love the word cleanse.

687
00:28:15,740 --> 00:28:18,220
 It's the same word for catharsis.

688
00:28:18,220 --> 00:28:23,860
 Most people, whenever they try to do some catharsis,

689
00:28:23,860 --> 00:28:26,180
 are trying to engage in activity

690
00:28:26,180 --> 00:28:28,180
 that changes their mentality.

691
00:28:28,180 --> 00:28:30,120
 They've got some stress or some raw emotions

692
00:28:30,120 --> 00:28:31,420
 that they need to work out.

693
00:28:31,420 --> 00:28:32,620
 And so what they'll do is they'll go to the gym

694
00:28:32,620 --> 00:28:33,460
 because they know, you know what,

695
00:28:33,460 --> 00:28:35,060
 I gotta sweat this thing out.

696
00:28:35,060 --> 00:28:36,980
 Or they're gonna pour themselves a bubble bath

697
00:28:36,980 --> 00:28:39,380
 and a glass of wine, and they're gonna lay back,

698
00:28:39,380 --> 00:28:41,020
 and they're gonna try to unwind in that space,

699
00:28:41,020 --> 00:28:41,900
 or they're gonna find a friend,

700
00:28:41,900 --> 00:28:44,740
 and they're gonna emotionally dump on that friend

701
00:28:44,740 --> 00:28:46,940
 because they've gotta vent out their frustrations.

702
00:28:46,940 --> 00:28:48,180
 Instead, or they'll go for a run

703
00:28:48,180 --> 00:28:49,660
 and they'll listen to Olivia Rodrigo

704
00:28:49,660 --> 00:28:51,540
 or whatever angsty teen music you like

705
00:28:51,540 --> 00:28:53,100
 because that's gonna help you process

706
00:28:53,100 --> 00:28:55,140
 everything that you're emoting inside.

707
00:28:55,140 --> 00:28:56,400
 I don't know what it is for you,

708
00:28:56,400 --> 00:29:01,400
 and yet the reality is we need to change our thinking.

709
00:29:01,400 --> 00:29:05,300
 That's what it means to go through a cathartic experience.

710
00:29:05,300 --> 00:29:07,700
 It's an activity that changes your mentality.

711
00:29:07,700 --> 00:29:11,520
 And Paul is saying to cleanse yourself

712
00:29:11,520 --> 00:29:15,580
 is to write your mindset.

713
00:29:15,580 --> 00:29:17,640
 I love the way one pastor said, he said,

714
00:29:17,640 --> 00:29:21,980
 "Your mindset is determined by what you set your mind on."

715
00:29:21,980 --> 00:29:25,600
 So let me ask you, what are you setting your mind on?

716
00:29:25,600 --> 00:29:28,960
 And I wanna challenge you, like really think about it.

717
00:29:28,960 --> 00:29:30,120
 Like don't just consider like,

718
00:29:30,120 --> 00:29:31,320
 well, what kind of music do I listen to?

719
00:29:31,320 --> 00:29:34,520
 No, why don't you consider what kind of lyrics

720
00:29:34,520 --> 00:29:36,760
 are found within the music you listen to?

721
00:29:36,760 --> 00:29:39,880
 Would you be comfortable reading those to your mom?

722
00:29:39,880 --> 00:29:41,520
 How about the shows you watch?

723
00:29:41,520 --> 00:29:44,880
 Not just, well, it's a teenage drama.

724
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:49,000
 Why don't you consider what's the message of that show?

725
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:53,260
 Would you be willing to defend that

726
00:29:53,260 --> 00:29:55,460
 in front of a room like this right now?

727
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:57,400
 Maybe it's not that.

728
00:29:57,400 --> 00:29:58,780
 Maybe it's your calendar.

729
00:29:58,780 --> 00:30:01,400
 Your schedule reflects your priorities.

730
00:30:01,400 --> 00:30:03,160
 If we looked at yours, would we actually see

731
00:30:03,160 --> 00:30:05,240
 that the things you claim to care about,

732
00:30:05,240 --> 00:30:07,600
 you back up with a life that cares about them?

733
00:30:08,720 --> 00:30:09,880
 Maybe it's not that.

734
00:30:09,880 --> 00:30:12,800
 When you and your friends talk about other people,

735
00:30:12,800 --> 00:30:14,600
 because listen, we know that you do.

736
00:30:14,600 --> 00:30:16,680
 When you and your friends get together

737
00:30:16,680 --> 00:30:18,280
 and you talk about other people,

738
00:30:18,280 --> 00:30:21,380
 would you be embarrassed to tell the person

739
00:30:21,380 --> 00:30:24,140
 you're talking about what exactly was said about them?

740
00:30:24,140 --> 00:30:28,540
 First Corinthians 15, 33 says, "Do not be deceived.

741
00:30:28,540 --> 00:30:32,380
 "Bad company ruins good morals."

742
00:30:32,380 --> 00:30:36,720
 If you wanna change your mindset, friend, listen,

743
00:30:36,720 --> 00:30:39,800
 you need to change the things that you set your mind on.

744
00:30:39,800 --> 00:30:40,780
 That's the first thing.

745
00:30:40,780 --> 00:30:43,320
 Cleanse yourself of dishonorable,

746
00:30:43,320 --> 00:30:45,400
 of that which is dishonorable.

747
00:30:45,400 --> 00:30:48,740
 The second thing Paul says is you need to flee youthful lusts.

748
00:30:48,740 --> 00:30:51,120
 That word flee is one of my favorite words in Greek

749
00:30:51,120 --> 00:30:53,160
 because it's the word fugo or fuego,

750
00:30:53,160 --> 00:30:57,960
 and the idea is it's the same root word behind fugitive.

751
00:30:57,960 --> 00:31:01,400
 It means to flee or to escape or to run away.

752
00:31:01,400 --> 00:31:04,140
 Now, no one's ever met a fugitive

753
00:31:04,140 --> 00:31:06,640
 who looked at them and said, "I don't know, man.

754
00:31:06,640 --> 00:31:08,280
 "I'm really struggling to get away

755
00:31:08,280 --> 00:31:09,560
 "from the people that are chasing me.

756
00:31:09,560 --> 00:31:11,720
 "Like, it's so hard not to go back."

757
00:31:11,720 --> 00:31:13,800
 No, they'd be a really bad fugitive

758
00:31:13,800 --> 00:31:15,440
 if that's the way they reacted.

759
00:31:15,440 --> 00:31:16,320
 What do they do?

760
00:31:16,320 --> 00:31:19,600
 They know, "My life depends on me running,

761
00:31:19,600 --> 00:31:21,840
 "getting away, escaping to the hills."

762
00:31:21,840 --> 00:31:24,240
 And so what they do is they run as fast

763
00:31:24,240 --> 00:31:26,600
 and as far as they can,

764
00:31:26,600 --> 00:31:29,720
 and we should do the same when it comes to sin

765
00:31:29,720 --> 00:31:31,560
 because just as their freedom depends on it,

766
00:31:31,560 --> 00:31:34,080
 your freedom depends on it too.

767
00:31:34,080 --> 00:31:36,440
 And yet here's the thing, as I talk to young adults,

768
00:31:36,440 --> 00:31:39,320
 every single week right down here at the foot of the stage,

769
00:31:39,320 --> 00:31:42,180
 I find within people just like yourself

770
00:31:42,180 --> 00:31:44,040
 that one of two things is often true.

771
00:31:44,040 --> 00:31:47,160
 One, we're not willing to run fast enough.

772
00:31:47,160 --> 00:31:50,400
 Well, Kylan, it's almost the holidays.

773
00:31:50,400 --> 00:31:52,200
 I know I've kind of got a problem with alcohol,

774
00:31:52,200 --> 00:31:53,420
 but everyone's coming in

775
00:31:53,420 --> 00:31:55,320
 and they're going to be opening up the liquor cabinet,

776
00:31:55,320 --> 00:31:57,320
 and I want to be able to enjoy what everybody's enjoying.

777
00:31:57,320 --> 00:31:59,280
 It's going to ruin my experience.

778
00:31:59,280 --> 00:32:02,320
 You're not willing to move fast enough then.

779
00:32:02,320 --> 00:32:04,200
 Others of you, you know, like,

780
00:32:04,200 --> 00:32:06,260
 "Man, we've crossed so many boundaries in my relationship,

781
00:32:06,260 --> 00:32:08,320
 "and he's not a believer, she's not a believer,

782
00:32:08,320 --> 00:32:10,240
 "and we're just toxic together."

783
00:32:10,240 --> 00:32:11,080
 But you know what?

784
00:32:11,080 --> 00:32:11,900
 Like, they've really shown promise.

785
00:32:11,900 --> 00:32:13,040
 I think that they may actually be able

786
00:32:13,040 --> 00:32:13,920
 to pull this thing through.

787
00:32:13,920 --> 00:32:15,400
 You know, we've had some spiritual conversations.

788
00:32:15,400 --> 00:32:16,960
 That gives me a lot of hope for the future.

789
00:32:16,960 --> 00:32:18,200
 And the reality is you need to break up.

790
00:32:18,200 --> 00:32:20,560
 You're just not willing to move fast enough.

